{# FlowDef execution — Security Scan PDCA (Snyk + Semgrep) #}

## Context
Scan target: {{ scan_target }}
Service pair: {{ service_pair | tojson }}
Dependency manifest reference: {{ dependency_manifest_ref }}
IaC rules reference: {{ iac_rules_ref }}
Previous cycle result: {{ previous_cycle_result | default({}) | tojson }}
Host identity (WebID): {{ replicant_webid }}
Delegation token: {{ delegation_token_ref }}

## How This Scan Came To Be (§P5.4 — PKO Process Axis)
This flow defines the procedural identity of the security scan. Each step is a verb,
not a noun — it answers "How did the scan come to be?" rather than "What is the scan?"
The noun identity (What) lives in the manifest registry (§P5.1 line 77);
the state identity (entity metadata) lives in DC+BIBO (§P5.4 line 94).

## Step 1 — Understand Direction (PDCA: Plan / Target)
Anchor: §P5.2 line 79 (5W1H — What + Why). Safe container (§P3.1) required.
Challenge: Security vulnerability detection across code + infrastructure.
Target state: Zero critical/high findings unreported; all dependency vulnerabilities mapped; all IaC misconfigurations flagged.
Measurement plan: Count critical/high findings before/after; dependency mapping coverage %; IaC rule hit rate.
Knowledge threshold: What the dependency graph reveals vs. what remains unknown (§P5.3 — bridge must justify existence by 5W1H).

## Step 2 — Grasp Current Condition (PDCA: Observe / Collect)
Services invoked (vertical slice — 2 only):
- Snyk: SAST + dependency scanning. Evidence: verified (public vendor docs). Unverified: dependency manifest mapping.
- Semgrep: SAST + IaC rules. Evidence: mechanism verified; domain bridge (FIBO analog for vulnerability scoring) unverified.
Data collection: Source code, dependency lock files, infrastructure definition files.
Observation constraints: No ambient authority (§P4.1). Every tool call carries DelegationToken.

## Step 3 — Scan Execution (PDCA: Do / Act)
Run Snyk scan (dependency graph + static rules).
Run Semgrep scan (AST pattern matching + IaC rules).
Cross-reference results (no cross-pod dispatch — PerPodToolBinding, §P4.1 line 65).
LLM boundary check (§P3.1): Prompt injection defense, role override defense, secret leakage defense — mandatory.

## Step 4 — State Recording (DC+BIBO State Axis — §P5.4 line 94)
Record scan results as entities with Dublin Core metadata (what + who + when) + BIBO bibliographic typing (entity relationships).
Bridge (optional — must justify by §P5.3): FIBO analog for vulnerability scoring / risk classification. If bridge cannot justify existence by 5W1H, reject — universal DC+BIBO core sufficient.
State entity fields:
  - result_id (entity identity)
  - scan_service (Snyk / Semgrep — noun)
  - finding_severity (critical / high / medium / low — classification)
  - dependency_package_ref (entity reference — unverified if dependency mapping incomplete)
  - iac_rule_ref (entity reference — verified mechanism, unverified domain bridge)
  - replicant_webid (author — §P12.1)
  - timestamp (DC — when)
  - cns_span_refs (links to regulatory axis — §P9.1)

## Step 5 — CNS Span Emission (§P9.1 — Canonical Namespace Invariant)
Every scan must emit canonical `cns.*` spans. Performative telemetry uses `hkask.*` (not `cns.*`); those are NOT registered.
Spans emitted:
  - cns.skill.scan (skill lifecycle — §P9.1 line 178)
  - cns.inference.scan_boundary (LLM boundary — mandatory per §P3.1; §P9.1 line 172)
  - cns.agent_pod.scan_session (pod-boundary session — §P9.1 line 183)
  - cns.cli.scan_invoked (command invocation — §P9.1 line 180)
Pattern: `tracing::info!(target: "cns.{domain}", operation = "...", ... , "CNS");`
Authority field: replicant WebID (§P9.1 line 200). No anonymous spans (§P12.1).

## Step 6 — Convergence / Loop Decision (§Pattern A — FlowDef convergence; kata-improvement reference)
Compute convergence metric: normalized improvement toward zero critical/high findings.
Threshold: 0.15 (§P5.4 — Heisenberg sampling; not truth claim).
If convergence not met → loop to Step 2 (max 3 iterations, §P5.3 minimalism — no extra loops without 5W1H justification).
If gas exceeded → abort (§P9.2 — energy regulation).
If timeout exceeded → retry (§P5.3 — retry must justify How).
If validation failure → abort (§P5.1 — registry is authoritative source of truth).

## Essentialism Justification for This FlowDef
Before writing: Does this answer at least one 5W1H?
- Who: replicant WebID (§P12.1) — handled by agent charter, referenced here.
- What: security scan (Snyk + Semgrep) — handled by manifest registry (§P5.1).
- When: PDCA cycle step — answered by this FlowDef (sequence, duration, schedule).
- Where: pod boundary (§P5.4 + §P4.1) — referenced (no cross-pod dispatch, DelegationToken, namespace PKO + DC+BIBO).
- Why: P3 generative space within safe container (§P3.1) — safe container controls mandatory.
- How: PKO flow + registry artifacts — answered by this template.
Result: All 6 answered. If any were missing, the FlowDef would fail the gate (§P5.3 line 92: "If 'none,' reject.").

## Security Container Controls (§P3.1 — Mandatory, Not Optional)
These controls are the floor, not the ceiling (§P3.1 line 60). They cannot be disabled.
Implemented via `hkask-guard` alignment:
- OWASP Top 10 for LLM Applications: LLM01 (Prompt Injection), LLM02 (Insecure Output Handling), LLM04 (Model DoS), LLM06 (Sensitive Information Disclosure)
- NIST AI RMF 1.0 (2023): Technical controls for validity, reliability, security, resiliency
- ENISA Multilayer Framework (2024): Security-by-design for AI systems
Every LLM boundary call in this flow passes through these controls.

